org.mfg.mdb.demo

Class Demo_02_PriceMDB.RandomCursor

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.mfg.mdb.demo.Demo_02_PriceMDB.RandomCursor
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Closeable, java.lang.AutoCloseable, ICursor<Demo_02_PriceMDB.Record>, IRandomCursor<Demo_02_PriceMDB.Record>
    Enclosing class:
    Demo_02_PriceMDB

    public final class Demo_02_PriceMDB.RandomCursor
extends java.lang.Object
implements IRandomCursor<Demo_02_PriceMDB.Record>

    This class provides a random-access cursor API. In case you want to retrieve sequential data, the best is to use a sequential cursor ( Demo_02_PriceMDB.Cursor).

    This cursor is the basic, faster and more controlled way to retrieve random data, it is used internally by other elements like the MDBList class.

    The common way to use a random cursor is: 

     Demo_02_PriceMDB mdb = ...;
 RandomCursor c = mdb.randomCursor(); 
 ...
 c.seek(somePosition);
 ...
 doSomething(c.time); 
 ...
 c.close();

    A random cursor contains the same "column fields" of a record, when the seek() method is called, the cursor "column fields" are updated.

    Warning: remember always to close the cursor, a common mistake is to try to delete a database when there are opened cursors: an open cursor blocks a file (at least in Windows).

    Usually you need only one random cursor per file, so probably you want to keep this cursor open while the session is alive, then you can use "defer" the cursor, this mean, the cursor will be closed automatically before to close the session. See the MDBSession.defer(ICursor) method.

    See Also:
    MDBSession.defer(ICursor), Demo_02_PriceMDB.Cursor
